def linear_congruential(x0, multiplier, shift, modulus, n, to_unit_interval=True):
    xs = np.empty(n + 1)
    xs[0] = x0
    for i in range(1, n + 1):
        xs[i] = (multiplier * xs[i - 1] + shift) % modulus

    if to_unit_interval:
        return xs[1:] / modulus
    return xs[1:]

# chi2 test of uniform distribution

def chi2_test(xs, n_classes):
    # n_classes should be chosen such that n_expected >= 5

    counts, _ = np.histogram(xs, bins=n_classes)
    
    expected_bin_count = xs.shape[0] / n_classes

    T = np.sum((counts - expected_bin_count)** 2 / expected_bin_count)

    # test stat follows chi2(k - 1), week 1 slide 10
    return 1 - chi2.cdf(T, n_classes - 1)

chi2_test(xs, 10)

# Kolmogorov test of uniform distribution

def empirical_cdf(samples):
    x = np.sort(samples)
    y = np.arange(1, len(x) + 1) / len(x)
    return x, y

xs_sorted, ecdf = empirical_cdf(xs)

error = ecdf - xs_sorted

max_error_idx = np.argmax(np.abs(error))
max_error = np.abs(error)[max_error_idx]

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 6))

ax1.plot(xs_sorted, ecdf, alpha=0.5)
ax1.plot(np.array([0, 1]), [0, 1], linestyle="--", alpha=0.5)

ax2.plot(xs_sorted, ecdf - xs_sorted)
ax2.plot([0, 1], [0, 0], linestyle="--")
ax2.plot([xs_sorted[max_error_idx], xs_sorted[max_error_idx]], [0, error[max_error_idx]], linestyle="--")

statistic, p_val = kstest(xs, 'uniform')

print("Statistic:", statistic)
print("P-value:", p_val)

def wald_wolfowitz(xs):
    mean = np.mean(xs)
    signs = xs > mean  # True if above mean, False if below or equal
    n_runs = np.sum(signs[1:] != signs[:-1]) + 1

    n1 = np.sum(signs)
    n2 = np.sum(~signs)

    mu = 2 * (n1 * n2) / (n1 + n2) + 1
    sigma2 = 2 * (n1 * n2 * (2 * n1 * n2 - n1 - n2)) / ((n1 + n2)** 2 * (n1 + n2 - 1))

    return norm.cdf(n_runs, loc=mu, scale=sigma2)

wald_wolfowitz(xs)

def count_run_lengths(data):
    data = np.asarray(data)
    up = np.zeros(6, dtype=int)
    down = np.zeros(6, dtype=int)
    n = len(data)
    i = 0

    while i < n - 1:
        run_len = 1
        if data[i+1] > data[i]:
            direction = 1
        elif data[i+1] < data[i]:
            direction = -1
        else:
            i += 1
            continue

        for j in range(i + 1, n):
            if direction == 1 and data[j] > data[j - 1]:
                run_len += 1
            elif direction == -1 and data[j] < data[j - 1]:
                run_len += 1
            else:
                break

        bin_idx = min(run_len, 6) - 1
        if direction == 1:
            up[bin_idx] += 1
        else:
            down[bin_idx] += 1

        i += run_len

    return up, down

count_run_lengths([1, 2, 3, 2, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8])

def knuth_up_down(xs):

    n = len(xs)

    up_runs, down_runs = count_run_lengths(xs)

    R = up_runs + down_runs

    A = np.array([
        [ 4529.4,  9044.9, 13568,  18091,  22615,  27892],
        [ 9044.9, 18097,   27139,  36187,  45234,  55789],
        [13568,   27139,   40721,  54281,  67852,  83685],
        [18091,   36187,   54281,  72414,  90470, 111580],
        [22615,   45234,   67852,  90470, 113262, 139476],
        [27892,   55789,   83685, 111580, 139476, 172860],
    ])

    B = np.array([
        1/6,
        5/24,
        11/120,
        19/720,
        29/5040,
        1/840
    ])

    Z = 1 / (n - 6) * (R - n * B).T @ A @ (R - n * B)

    return chi2.cdf(Z, df=6)

knuth_up_down(xs)

from itertools import islice

def linear_congruential_gen(seed, multiplier, shift, modulus, to_unit_interval=True):
    while True:
        seed = (multiplier * seed + shift) % modulus
        yield seed / modulus
    
gen = linear_congruential_gen(seed, a, c, M)

def take_n(gen, n):
    return np.array(list(islice(gen, n)))

N = 10_000

ps = np.empty(N)

for i in range(N):
    ps[i] = chi2_test(take_n(gen, 1000), 50)

plt.title("p-value distribution")
plt.hist(ps, density=True, bins=20)
plt.gca().axhline(1.0, linestyle="--", color="g")
plt.show()
